{
  "texts": [
    "For range queries, the query box is transformed to intervals of Z-addresses, such that the underlying 1-D learned index (e.g., an RMI) can be queried to efficiently locate the query box in storage.",
    "HM-Index [83] and SLBRIN [82] are two similar projection-based indexes that use the Hilbert-curve and Geo-Hash, respectively, as their projection functions.",
    "Wazi [64] and LMSFC [28] are two improved versions of the original ZM-Index by adaptively optimizing the Z-order curve using query workloads.",
    "ML-Index [19] adopts an improved iDistance function as the projection function, which is typically used to index high dimensional data [38].",
    "As shown in Fig. 3, given a set of m reference points (RP) r 1, • • •, r m, which is usually obtained by k-means, the input data X are partitioned into m disjoint subsets based on the distance to each RP."
  ]
}